	faithHeading="Faith and the Bible in Nigeria"
	faithBodyHtml={`<p>Nigeria is one of the most religious nations on earth, and almost evenly divided: roughly <strong>46% Christian</strong> and <strong>46% Muslim</strong>. With some 110 million Christians, Nigeria has one of the largest Christian populations in the world &mdash; its churches among the most vibrant anywhere.</p><p>The Bible has deep roots here. The Bible Society of Nigeria has translated Scripture into <strong>27 Nigerian languages</strong> &mdash; Yoruba in 1884, Igbo in 1906, Hausa in 1932 &mdash; with more underway. Yet most Nigerians read the Bible in English or a few major tongues, while over 500 languages and 120 million Pidgin speakers still wait for the Father&rsquo;s heart in their own words.</p><p>For all this faith, and across all this division, the deepest need is the same: to know God not as a distant judge to fear, but as a Father who draws near. That is what the Father&rsquo;s Heart Bible&trade; was made to reveal.</p>`}
